observations.recommendation:
We have recommended the Municipal Mayor to instruct the following:

For the MHO or RHU personnel to furnish copy of claims to the Municipal Accountant in order to set up Due from GOCCs account – Receivable from PhilHealth. This would help in the monitoring of claims pending to be paid by PhilHealth;


Management should present copies of the official receipts and the corresponding JEVs for the series of official receipts claimed to have already been issued by the Municipal Accountant. They should also consult PhilHealth regarding the deficiencies that need to be addressed or submitted in order to release the claims from CY 2019 to 2022;

For the Municipal Treasurer to make Certification on the Receipt of Claims from PhilHealth via bank transfer in lieu of an Official Receipt to support the JEV as evidence;

For the Municipal Accountant to:

check and review her records vis-à-vis the bank statements on whether or not she was able to make JEV for all the claims transferred to the RHU accounts;

record the receivables from PhilHealth, to wit:

Account Titles:	
	Due from GOCCs	      134,500.00	
		Government Equity	134,500.00

	To record receivables from PhilHealth for CY 2019 to 2022.

	maintain subsidiary ledger for Due from GOCCs account pertaining to RHU claims to PhilHealth.

The BAC through the Secretariat to ensure that all bidding documents are secured and complete, and to transmit the same to the COA Office for auditorial contract review. Furthermore, we recommend the submission of the lacking documents pertaining to the Rehabilitation of Farm-to-Market Road project;


The Municipal Engineer prepare documents relative to the project such as but not limited to Program of Work (POW) and Statement of Work Accomplished; and

The Municipal Accountant, Municipal Treasurer, and Municipal Agriculturist to ensure that disbursements are supported with complete and accurate documents before effecting payment for any financial support given to the tobacco farmers.

We have recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the Municipal Accountant to:
Coordinate with the concerned source agency to (a) Secure a copy of the MOAs or any documents from the concerned agencies, if no copies are available within the concerned officers-in-charge, to support the payables as well as details such as terms and conditions of the grant to identify the nature of such payables and (b) furnish a copy of the said agreement to the Audit Team;
Coordinate with the Municipal Budget Officer and the MPDC on the projects implemented or to be implemented relating to the long outstanding payables under Due to NGAs by reviewing the MOAs and any related documents as to the terms and conditions of the grant;
Take necessary actions for projects already completed, such as liquidation or remittance of the remaining balance of payables depending on the agreement between the Municipality and the NGAs;
Prepare a reconciliation report to identify the cause of the abnormal balance of the account totaling ₱16,134.92 and prepare the necessary adjusting entry to properly reflect the balance of the affected accounts;
Transfer the balance of LGU’s share from tobacco excise tax under Trust Fund to the General Fund and prepare the adjusting journal entry for the total unexpended balance of LGU’s Share from tobacco excise tax and the Share from PCSO using the proforma entry below:
Adjusting entry under General Fund if the books of the Municipal Government is not yet closed and receipts pertain to current year:
Adjusting entry under General Fund if the book of the Municipality is already closed:
Coordinate with the Municipal Treasurer to remit the remaining balance of the share of DPWH on the building permits and other related fees to the recipients specified under the procedural guidelines provided in DPWH-DILG JMC No. 001 dated July 4, 2015; and
Create a monitoring report on these payables indicating the status, terms and conditions of the agreement, date of grant, aging of payables, and other details pertaining to the utilization, liquidation, and remittance for a more efficient and effective monitoring.

We have recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to:
Create a monitoring schedule and reconcile the Due to BIR, GSIS, PAG-IBIG, and PhilHealth accounts with the actual amounts withheld based on the filed tax returns, statement of account, and loan amortization schedule from respective agencies, to identify the under and over-remittances incurred from prior years until the current year;
Observe the timely remittance and recording of tax dues/withheld from employees/suppliers, premium contributions of both employer and employee, as well as the loan repayments to the concerned Offices, as the case may be, as prescribed by BIR, GSIS, PAG-IBIG, and PhilHealth in order to avoid possible penalties;
Remit all taxes withheld, premium contributions, and loan repayment intact on or before the deadline as provided in the rules and regulations set by the BIR, GSIS, PAG-IBIG, and PhilHealth to avoid penalties, surcharges, and interests from delayed remittances.

We have recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the Municipal Treasurer to:

Transmit all unsubmitted cancelled checks including those accumulated prior to CY 2023;


Ensure all original copies of cancelled checks are accounted for and submitted in the month they were cancelled to the Auditor’s Office pursuant to Section 59 of NGAS for LGUs;

Reports and documents for submission should be clearly identified and communicated to the responsible individuals to ensure that no reports or documents are overlooked or left unsubmitted;

Always disclose cancelled check/s in the cashbook to establish monitoring following strictly the numerical sequence of the checks; and


Finally, reports and documents for submission should be clearly identified and communicated to the responsible individuals to ensure that no reports or documents are overlooked or left unsubmitted.

The BAC through the Secretariat to ensure that all bidding documents are secured and complete and transmit the same to the COA Office for auditorial contract review. 


The Municipal Engineer to prepare documents relative to the project such as but not limited to POW and SWA;

The Municipal Accountant to ensure that disbursements are supported with complete and accurate documents before effecting payment.

7.9  We recommend the Municipal Mayor to instruct the following:
For the MHO or RHU personnel to furnish copy of claims to the Municipal Accountant in order to set up Due from GOCCs account – Receivable from PhilHealth. This would help in the monitoring of claims pending to be paid by PhilHealth;
Management should present copies of the official receipts and the corresponding JEVs for the series of official receipts claimed to have already been issued by the Municipal Accountant. They should also consult PhilHealth regarding the deficiencies that need to be addressed or submitted in order to release the claims from CY 2019 to 2022;
For the Municipal Treasurer to make Certification on the Receipt of Claims from PhilHealth via bank transfer in lieu of an Official Receipt to support the JEV as evidence;
For the Municipal Accountant to:
check and review her records vis-à-vis the bank statements on whether or not she was able to make JEV for all the claims transferred to the RHU accounts;
record the receivables from PhilHealth, to wit:
maintain subsidiary ledger for Due from GOCCs account pertaining to RHU claims to PhilHealth.

9.7  With the foregoing observation, we have recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the Municipal Treasurer to:
Transmit all unsubmitted cancelled checks including those accumulated prior to CY 2023;
Ensure all original copies of cancelled checks are accounted for and submitted in the month they were cancelled to the Auditor’s Office pursuant to Section 59 of NGAS for LGUs;
Reports and documents for submission should be clearly identified and communicated to the responsible individuals to ensure that no reports or documents are overlooked or left unsubmitted;
Always disclose cancelled check/s in the cashbook to establish monitoring following strictly the numerical sequence of the checks; and
Finally, reports and documents for submission should be clearly identified and communicated to the responsible individuals to ensure that no reports or documents are overlooked or left unsubmitted.

We recommended and management agreed to the following:

To direct the Municipal Treasurer to stop the practice of issuing torn cash tickets;

To direct the Market Administrator or his authorized representative to conduct surprise inspection on the proper issuance of cash tickets.

We recommended and management agreed to instruct the Municipal Treasurer the following:

Maintain separate logbook or folder for all the issuances of accountable forms to barangays; 

Strict monitoring of CTC collections and remittances and implement daily or weekly and intact turn-over of collections to the Municipal Treasury. The fifty percent (50%) share of Barangay from issuances of CTC will be processed by the Municipal Treasury Office, and not the barangay remitting only the fifty percent (50%) share to the Municipal Treasury Office.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to direct the:

Bids and Award Committee to submit the Purchase Order/Contract Agreement with all the complete bidding document within five working days upon perfection as provided in the COA Circular No. 2009-001, and; 

Accounting Office to ensure that all the necessary documentary required under COA Circular 2012-001 for the completeness and legality of the claims for the payment of procurement are attached.

We recommended and management agreed to the following:
To direct the Municipal Treasurer to stop the practice of issuing torn cash tickets;
To direct the Market Administrator or his authorized representative to conduct surprise inspection on the proper issuance of cash tickets.

We recommended and management agreed to instruct the Municipal Treasurer the following:
Maintain separate logbook or folder for all the issuances of accountable forms to barangays;
Strict monitoring of CTC collections and remittances and implement daily or weekly and intact turn-over of collections to the Municipal Treasury. The fifty percent (50%) share of Barangay from issuances of CTC will be processed by the Municipal Treasury Office, and not the barangay remitting only the fifty percent (50%) share to the Municipal Treasury Office.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to direct the:
Bids and Award Committee to submit the Purchase Order/Contract Agreement with all the complete bidding document within five working days upon perfection as provided in the COA Circular No. 2009-001, and;
Accounting Office to ensure that all the necessary documentary required under COA Circular 2012-001 for the completeness and legality of the claims for the payment of procurement are attached.

In view of the foregoing observations, we have recommended the following:

Require the BAC Chairman to submit copies of POs irrespective of amount and all related documents forming part thereof to COA within (5) working days upon issuance of POs;

Instruct the Supply Officer to notify the Auditor’s Office within 24 hours from acceptance of deliveries as per COA Circular No. 96-010 to enable the Auditor to conduct its inspection;


Monitor strict compliance to said regulations and enforce sanctions for non-compliance, if necessary.
